{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>The Salmonella typhimurium Surface Presentation of Antigens M gene (SpaM) is one of 12 that form a cluster responsible for invasion properties [[cite:PUB00001240]]. The gene product is required for entry by the bacterium into epithelial cells, and is thus considered to be a virulence factor [[cite:PUB00001240]]. Other Spa genes in the cluster are related to invasion (Inv) genes in similar Salmonella and Shigella species [[cite:PUB00005977]], and flagella biosynthesis genes in Helicobacter pylori [[cite:PUB00005978]].</p>\n\n<p>A homologue of this protein has been found recently in Salmonella enterica [[cite:PUB00005979]]. The protein, named InvI, is required by the organism to gain access to mammalian epithelial cells, and cellular mutants (InvI-) failed to successfully infect these cells. It has also been found that the inv-spa loci of this particular species encode for a type III protein secretion system, essential in the bacterium's host cell invasion process [[cite:PUB00005980]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with nil, :member-databases {"pfam" {"PF02090" "Salmonella surface presentation of antigen gene type M protein"}, "prints" {"PR01227" "SSPAMPROTEIN"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Salmonella surface presentation of antigen M protein", "short" "Salm_SPAgM"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 0, "domain_architectures" 2, "proteomes" 51, "taxa" 622, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 707, "sets" 0, "proteins" 706, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 591}, "pathways" 0}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {}, :set-info nil, :accession "IPR002954", :literature {"PUB00001240" {"URL" nil, "issue" "10", "authors" ["Groisman EA" "Ochman H."], "ISO_journal" "EMBO J.", "DOI_URL" "http://www.pubmedcentral.nih.gov/articlerender.fcgi?tool=EBI&pubmedid=8404849", "medline_journal"